## RESEARCH ATTRIBUTION

This repository contains educational materials and research implementations based on:

1. **Original DBSCAN Algorithm**: 
   Ester, M., Kriegel, H. P., Sander, J., & Xu, X. (1996). 
   "A density-based algorithm for discovering clusters in large spatial databases with noise." 
   In Proceedings of the Second International Conference on Knowledge Discovery and Data Mining (KDD-96), 
   pages 226-231. AAAI Press.

2. **Research Materials**: 
   Some datasets and research methodologies may have been derived from or inspired by 
   materials available from biolab.si and other academic institutions. Users are 
   encouraged to verify the original sources of any specific datasets or research 
   materials they intend to use for academic or commercial purposes.

## TERMS OF USE

### Educational Use
- This repository is primarily intended for educational and research purposes
- All implementations are provided for learning and understanding the DBSCAN algorithm
- Users are encouraged to cite the original DBSCAN paper when using this material academically

### Research and Academic Use
- When using this repository for academic research, please:
  - Cite the original DBSCAN paper (Ester et al., 1996)
  - Acknowledge this repository if it significantly contributed to your work
  - Verify and cite original sources for any specific datasets used
  - Follow your institution's guidelines for software and data attribution

### Commercial Use
- Commercial use is permitted under the MIT license terms
- Users should independently verify the licensing terms of any datasets used
- No warranty is provided for commercial applications

### Data Attribution
- Real-world datasets included in this repository may have specific attribution requirements
- Users are responsible for verifying the original sources and licensing terms of datasets
- Some datasets may be synthetic or derived from publicly available sources
- When in doubt, contact the repository maintainers for clarification on data sources

### Modifications and Derivatives
- Modifications and derivative works are permitted under MIT license terms
- Please maintain attribution to original sources when creating derivative works
- Consider contributing improvements back to the community

